.TH LU\-RULE 1 "2026-04-27" "logicutils 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lu\-rule \- match a target against pattern rules with backtracking
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lu\-rule
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fITARGET\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lu\-rule
selects a build rule that produces \fITARGET\fR. A rule file is a
sequence of rule blocks separated by lines containing only
.BR --- .
Each block is a colon\-separated set of fields:

.RS
.nf
pattern: align\-{X}\-{Y}.bam
deps:    {X}.fa {Y}.fa
recipe:  align {X}.fa {Y}.fa > align\-{X}\-{Y}.bam
goal:    X != Y
.fi
.RE

The
.I pattern
field is matched against \fITARGET\fR using the same wildcard syntax as
.BR lu\-match (1).
If \fIgoal\fR is present it must evaluate to true under the bindings
produced by the match. \fIdeps\fR and \fIrecipe\fR are template\-expanded
with those bindings.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-rulefile=\fIFILE\fR
Rule file. If omitted, rules are read from standard input.
.TP
.B \-\-all
Emit every matching rule, not just the first.
.TP
.B \-\-backtrack
If the first matching rule fails its goal, try the next rule. Implied
by
.BR \-\-all .
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Print the expanded recipe to standard output and exit.
.TP
.BI \-\-format= FORMAT
Output format: \fIplain\fR, \fIjson\fR, \fItsv\fR, \fIcsv\fR, \fItoml\fR,
\fIshell\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
0 on a successful match, 1 if no rule matches, 2 on error.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lu\-match (1),
.BR lu\-query (1),
.BR lu\-deps (1)
.SH AUTHOR
NEWSNIPER.
